Reason: To predict the melting point of m-bromoiodobenzene, we consider the effects of the functional groups (bromo and iodo) attached to the benzene ring. Basic unit, benzene, has a melting point of 5.5°C. Generally, halogens attached to an aromatic ring increase the melting point due to the increased molecular weight and size, which leads to higher London dispersion forces. A bromo group generally increases the melting point of benzene by approximately 20°C, and an iodo group by approximately 40°C because iodine has a larger atomic mass and size compared to bromine. However, these effects are not simply additive because there is also polarizability and possible intramolecular interactions between the two different halogens that could result in an overall lower melting point. Due to the interaction and larger size of the substituents causing steric hindrance, the increase might not be as high as the sum of individual effects.
